related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: Scheduled tasks: Regularly scheduled tasks like oil changes in vehicles, filter replacements in HVAC systems, or lubrication of machinery.
Inspections: Routine checks of equipment to identify potential issues before they become major problems, such as inspecting machinery for wear and tear.
Cleaning: Maintaining cleanliness to prevent buildup of dirt and debris, which can cause equipment malfunctions or damage.
Calibration: Ensuring equipment is properly calibrated to maintain accuracy and optimal performance.
Software updates: Installing updates to keep software running smoothly and securely.

Preventative maintenance examples: According to FaultFixers, tasks related to energy efficiency and sustainability, like implementing building automation systems or retrofitting HVAC systems with energy-efficient components, are also considered preventive maintenance.
Repairing broken equipment: Fixing malfunctioning machinery, electrical systems, or plumbing.
Replacing damaged parts: Swapping out worn-out or broken components of equipment.
Emergency repairs: Addressing unexpected breakdowns or failures to restore functionality quickly.
Buildings: . Opens in new tabRoutine tasks like cleaning, landscaping, and snow removal, as well as addressing issues like roof leaks or electrical problems.
Vehicles: . Opens in new tabRoutine maintenance like oil changes, tire rotations, and brake inspections, as well as addressing unexpected repairs.
Machinery: . Opens in new tabLubricating moving parts, replacing worn-out components, and troubleshooting malfunctions.
Software: . Opens in new tabUpdating software, fixing bugs, and implementing security patches.
Frequency: Maintenance schedules vary depending on the asset and its usage. Some tasks are performed daily, others weekly, monthly, or even less frequently.
Cost: Preventive maintenance can help reduce the cost of corrective maintenance by preventing major breakdowns.
Safety: Regular maintenance ensures that equipment and facilities are safe to use.
Efficiency: Well-maintained assets operate more efficiently, reducing energy consumption and downtime.

text_blocks.snippet: Maintenance refers to the activities and processes involved in keeping something in good working order, whether it's a machine, a building, or even a person's health. It encompasses actions like inspecting, cleaning, repairing, and replacing components to prevent breakdowns, ensure functionality, and extend the lifespan of the item being maintained.
snippet_highlighted_words: the activities and processes involved in keeping something in good working order, whether it's a machine, a building, or even a person's health

list.title: Keeping things in good working order:
list.snippet: This is the core purpose of maintenance. It ensures that things continue to function as intended and don't fall into disrepair.

list.title: Preventing breakdowns and failures:
list.snippet: Maintenance activities help identify and address potential problems before they cause major issues, saving time and money.

list.title: Extending lifespan:
list.snippet: By regularly servicing and maintaining items, their useful life can be significantly extended.
Preventive Maintenance: Scheduled activities like inspections, cleaning, and lubrication to prevent problems before they occur.
Corrective Maintenance: Repairs or replacements performed after a problem has already occurred.
Predictive Maintenance: Using data and analysis to anticipate potential failures and schedule maintenance proactively.
In a car: Changing the oil, rotating tires, and replacing brake pads are all forms of maintenance.
In a building: Cleaning, painting, repairing leaky faucets, and replacing light bulbs are examples of building maintenance.
In a computer: Updating software, cleaning out temporary files, and replacing failing components are computer maintenance tasks.

text_blocks.snippet: In essence, maintenance is about taking care of things to ensure they continue to function properly and effectively over time.
